Use the window "focus" event (and "blur") to detect the browser window/tab gaining/losing focus. document's "focus" doesn't bubble, so if you want an event that bubbles on the document use "focusin". You can also use the document "visibilitychange" event / document.hidden to detect tab visibility.

Also fix your useEffect cleanup (you must return the cleanup function).

Examples:

- Use window focus/blur (recommended for window/tab focus changes)
```js
useEffect(() => {
  const handleFocus = () => {
    if (ref.current) ref.current.focus();
  };
  const handleBlur = () => {
    // optional: handle window lost focus
  };

  window.addEventListener('focus', handleFocus);
  window.addEventListener('blur', handleBlur);

  return () => {
    window.removeEventListener('focus', handleFocus);
    window.removeEventListener('blur', handleBlur);
  };
}, []); // run once; ref is stable
```

- Use document.visibilitychange to detect tab visibility (works when tab is hidden/visible)
```js
useEffect(() => {
  const onVisibilityChange = () => {
    if (!document.hidden && ref.current) ref.current.focus();
  };
  document.addEventListener('visibilitychange', onVisibilityChange);
  return () => document.removeEventListener('visibilitychange', onVisibilityChange);
}, []);
```

- Use document focusin if you need to listen for element focus events that bubble
```js
useEffect(() => {
  const onFocusIn = (e) => {
    // e.target is the focused element that bubbled up
  };
  document.addEventListener('focusin', onFocusIn);
  return () => document.removeEventListener('focusin', onFocusIn);
}, []);
```

Pick window "focus"/"blur" for window/tab focus changes; use "visibilitychange" for tab visibility; use "focusin" for element focus events that bubble.

Use the window "focus" (and optionally "blur") events. In a Tauri desktop/webview app, the webview will receive normal window focus/blur events when the user switches apps, so window.addEventListener("focus", ...) is the simplest and most reliable way to run a callback when the user comes back.

Also optionally: document.visibilitychange (document.hidden) can detect tab/window visibility changes and is a good fallback, and Tauri also emits platform-specific window events you can inspect in the Tauri docs if you need native hooks ‚Äî but in most cases window focus/blur is enough.

Fixed React example (with cleanup and a stable effect):

```js
useEffect(() => {
  // focus immediately if the ref is present
  ref.current?.focus();

  const handleFocus = () => ref.current?.focus();

  window.addEventListener('focus', handleFocus);
  window.addEventListener('blur', () => {
    // optional: do something on blur
  });

  return () => {
    window.removeEventListener('focus', handleFocus);
    // remove blur listener if you added one separately
  };
}, []); // run once; ref is a ref and doesn't need to be in deps
```

Alternative using visibilitychange:

```js
useEffect(() => {
  const onVisibilityChange = () => {
    if (!document.hidden) ref.current?.focus();
  };
  document.addEventListener('visibilitychange', onVisibilityChange);
  return () => document.removeEventListener('visibilitychange', onVisibilityChange);
}, []);
```

If you need to use Tauri-specific APIs, check the Tauri docs for window events ‚Äî but starting with window.addEventListener('focus', ...) is recommended.

