My code never sets loading to false... but it is getting reset to false immediatly after it gets set to true when I log it

What's happening

- setLoading(true) is asynchronous ‚Äî if you log loading immediately after calling setLoading(true) you'll still see the old value (React updates state on the next render).
- Your handleSendMessage never calls setLoading(false). That means loading should remain true until something else sets it false ‚Äî but from your description it appears you're just logging right after setLoading and seeing false (the old value), not that React flipped it back.
- Fix: setLoading(false) in a finally block so it always runs after invoke finishes (success or error).

Suggested fixes

1) Update handleSendMessage to always clear loading:

```ts
const handleSendMessage = async (incoming: Omit<Message, "_id">) => {
  setLoading(true);
  try {
    await invoke("save_message", { message: incoming });
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
  } finally {
    setLoading(false);
  }
};
```

2) If you want to observe when loading actually changes (for debugging), use a useEffect:

```ts
useEffect(() => {
  console.log("loading changed:", loading);
}, [loading]);
```

3) Minor improvement to the listen cleanup ‚Äî avoid returning a cleanup that depends on a promise resolution by creating the listener and storing the unlisten function:

```ts
useEffect(() => {
  let unlisten: (() => void) | null = null;
  let mounted = true;

  listen<Message>("message_created", (event) => {
    // this returns a Promise that resolves to an unlisten function
  }).then((u) => {
    if (mounted) unlisten = u;
  });

  return () => {
    mounted = false;
    if (unlisten) unlisten();
  };
}, []);
```

Or more compactly:

```ts
useEffect(() => {
  let stop: (() => void) | undefined;
  (async () => {
    stop = await listen<Message>("message_created", (event) => {
      setMessages(prev => [...prev, event.payload]);
    });
  })();
  return () => stop && stop();
}, []);
```

Other notes

- If multiple send calls can overlap, consider a counter or separate loading state per message to avoid racing.
- If you try to set state on an unmounted component, guard with a mounted flag.
- React.StrictMode can cause double-mount behavior in dev ‚Äî that can confuse logging but not the fix above.

