Short answer: import it or use new URL. Both are resolved by Vite at build time and will work in a Tauri bundle.

Examples (assume file is src/assets/my-image.png):

1) Import (most common)
```tsx
// src/components/MyComponent.tsx
import React from "react";
import myImage from "../assets/my-image.png";

export const MyComponent = () => (
  <img src={myImage} alt="My image" style={{ width: 200 }} />
);
```

2) new URL (useful for dynamic resolution)
```tsx
// src/components/MyComponent.tsx
import React from "react";

export const MyComponent = () => {
  const src = new URL("../assets/my-image.png", import.meta.url).href;
  return <img src={src} alt="My image" style={{ width: 200 }} />;
};
```

Notes
- If you instead place images in the public/ folder (public/assets/...), reference them by absolute path: <img src="/assets/my-image.png" />.
- In TypeScript you may need asset module declarations (if not already present). Add to src/vite-env.d.ts or a global .d.ts:
  declare module "*.png";
  declare module "*.jpg";
  declare module "*.svg";
- Both approaches are handled by Vite and will be bundled into the Tauri app ‚Äî nothing extra needed for packaging.

Pick whichever fits your use case (import for static imports, new URL for dynamic file resolution).

Yes ‚Äî that works. When you import an image file with Vite, the imported value is a URL string you can use directly as the src of an <img>.

Example (TypeScript + React):
```tsx
// src/components/MyComponent.tsx
import React from "react";
import MyImage from "../assets/img.png"; // path relative to this file

export const MyComponent = () => (
  <img src={MyImage} alt="My image" style={{ width: 200 }} />
);
```

Things to know
- In Vite the import resolves to a URL (string). You can console.log(MyImage) to see it.
- In TypeScript you may need an asset module declaration (if you get a TS error). Add to src/vite-env.d.ts:
  declare module "*.png";
  declare module "*.jpg";
  declare module "*.jpeg";
  declare module "*.svg";
- Small images may be inlined as data URLs by Vite if they are below build.assetsInlineLimit (default 4096 bytes). To change that or prevent inlining, adjust vite.config.js build.assetsInlineLimit.
- Path is relative to the importing file. If import fails, check the correct relative path and restart the dev server if needed.
- For SVGs you can also use React-specific imports (SVGR) if you want them as components (requires plugin/config).
- Nothing extra is required for packaging with Tauri ‚Äî Vite will bundle the asset and the app will use the generated URL.

That should be all you need ‚Äî import and use it in the img tag as shown.

