Nice ‚Äî that sounds like a useful app. A few practical recommendations and quick code snippets to help you build it safely and robustly.

High-level design / security
- Do requests from the Rust side (Tauri backend), not the frontend, so the API key never lands in the renderer process or the shipped JS bundle.
- For development you can use an environment variable (OPENAI_API_KEY). For production you should let the user provide their key and store it securely (OS keychain). Don‚Äôt hardcode or bundle keys.
- For storing the user-provided key: either prompt the user on first run and save it in the OS keychain (keyring/keytar) or use a secure storage plugin. On Rust side the keyring crate works well.
- Consider streaming responses for a snappy chat feel (OpenAI supports streaming). You can stream in Rust and emit partial updates to the frontend with tauri::AppHandle::emit_all (or Window::emit).

Rust examples

1) Read API key from env (dev) and make a simple (non-streaming) OpenAI call:

Cargo.toml (deps)
- reqwest = { version = "0.11", features = ["json", "rustls-tls"] }
- serde = { version = "1.0", features = ["derive"] }
- tauri = { ... }

Rust command:
