use keyring::Keyring;

fn save_api_key(service: &str, username: &str, key: &str) -> Result<(), keyring::Error> {
  let kr = Keyring::new(service, username);
  kr.set_password(key)
}

fn get_api_key(service: &str, username: &str) -> Result<String, keyring::Error> {
  let kr = Keyring::new(service, username);
  kr.get_password()
}
```
On the frontend provide a small form that invokes a tauri command to store the key (no echoing it back to renderer).

3) Streaming example idea (emit partial tokens to UI)
- Use reqwest::Client::post(...).send().await?.bytes_stream() and parse SSE-style chunks from OpenAI when "stream": true, then emit partials with app.emit_all("message_chunk", chunk).
- Frontend already has a listener pattern; listen for "message_chunk" and append to the last Bot message.

Frontend
- You already have listen("message_created", ...) ‚Äî keep doing that.
- If you stream, also listen for "message_chunk" or "message_stream_end" to update UI progressively.

Other practical notes
- Model choice: gpt-3.5-turbo is much cheaper than GPT-4. Consider exposing model selection to the user.
- Token usage / cost: show estimated token usage or confirm before long requests.
- Concurrency: guard against multiple overlapping sends or show per-message loading indicators instead of a single global boolean if you want multiple parallel chats.
- Packaging: nothing special for packaging as long as you don‚Äôt bundle keys. If you used env var for dev, tell users how to set the env var or provide a UI to paste the key.
- Logging: never log the secret key.

