Nice ‚Äî below is a practical streaming implementation you can drop into your Tauri backend. The approach:

- Insert the user message (same as you already do) and emit it.
- Generate a temporary client-side id (UUID) and emit a "message_stream_start" event with that id so the frontend can render a placeholder Bot message immediately.
- Call OpenAI with "stream": true and parse the SSE-like response, emitting "message_chunk" events as tokens arrive (payload includes the temp id).
- When the stream ends, insert the final bot message into your DB, emit the normal "message_created" with the real DB id, and emit "message_stream_end" mapping temp -> final id so the frontend can replace the placeholder.

This avoids needing a DB update API and keeps the frontend in sync.

Rust code (replace your save_message with this):

```rust
use deeb::*;
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use serde_json::Value;
use tauri::State;
use tauri_plugin_http::reqwest;
use futures::StreamExt;
use uuid::Uuid;

use crate::app_state::AppState;

#[derive(Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub enum MessageRole {
    User,
    Bot,
}

#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, Collection)]
pub struct Message {
    _id: String,
    text: String,
    role: MessageRole,
    _created_at: String,
}

#[derive(Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct CreateMessageInput {
    text: String,
    role: MessageRole,
}

// For non-streaming full response parsing (unused for stream)
#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, Debug)]
struct ChatGptRequest {
    model: String,
    messages: Vec<ChatGptMessage>,
    stream: Option<bool>,
}

#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, Debug)]
struct ChatGptMessage {
    role: String,
    content: String,
}

// For streaming events parsing
#[derive(Deserialize, Debug)]
struct StreamResponse {
    choices: Vec<StreamChoice>,
}

#[derive(Deserialize, Debug)]
struct StreamChoice {
    delta: Option<Delta>,
}

#[derive(Deserialize, Debug)]
struct Delta {
    content: Option<String>,
    role: Option<String>,
}

#[tauri::command]
pub async fn save_message(
    app_handle: tauri::AppHandle,
    app_state: State<'_, AppState>,
    message: CreateMessageInput,
) -> tauri::Result<Message> {
    // 1) Save the user message and emit it (unchanged)
    let saved_user_msg =
        Message::insert_one::<CreateMessageInput>(&app_state.db, message.clone(), None).await?;
    app_handle.emit_all("message_created", &saved_user_msg).unwrap();

    // 2) Build history context (unchanged from yours)
    let mut history = Message::find_many(
        &app_state.db,
        Query::All,
        Some(FindManyOptions {
            skip: Some(0),
            limit: Some(20),
            order: vec![FindManyOrder {
                property: "_created_at".to_string(),
                direction: OrderDirection::Descending,
            }]
            .into(),
        }),
        None,
    )
    .await?
    .unwrap_or_default();

    history.reverse();

    let chat_messages: Vec<ChatGptMessage> = history
        .iter()
        .map(|m| ChatGptMessage {
            role: match m.role {
                MessageRole::User => "user".to_string(),
                MessageRole::Bot => "assistant".to_string(),
            },
            content: m.text.clone(),
        })
        .collect();

    // 3) Prepare streaming request
    let client = reqwest::Client::new();
    let req_body = ChatGptRequest {
        model: "gpt-3.5-turbo".into(),
        messages: chat_messages,
        stream: Some(true),
    };

    let api_key = std::env::var("OPENAI_API_KEY").expect("OPENAI_API_KEY not set");

    let resp = client
        .post("https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions")
        .bearer_auth(api_key)
        .json(&req_body)
        .send()
        .await
        .map_err(|e| tauri::api::Error::from(e.to_string()))?;

    // If non-success status, parse error:
    if !resp.status().is_success() {
        let txt = resp.text().await.unwrap_or_default();
        return Err(tauri::api::Error::msg(format!(
            "OpenAI error: {}",
            txt
        )));
    }

    // 4) Emit stream start with a temp id so frontend can render immediately
    let temp_id = Uuid::new_v4().to_string();
    let start_payload = serde_json::json!({
        "id": temp_id,
        "role": "Bot",
        "text": ""
    });
    app_handle
        .emit_all("message_stream_start", start_payload)
        .unwrap();

    // 5) Read the bytes stream and parse SSE style "data: {...}" chunks
    let mut stream = resp.bytes_stream();
    let mut buffer = String::new();
    let mut collected_text = String::new();

    while let Some(item) = stream.next().await {
        let bytes = item.map_err(|e| tauri::api::Error::from(e.to_string()))?;
        let chunk_str = String::from_utf8_lossy(&bytes);
        buffer.push_str(&chunk_str);

        // OpenAI SSE events are separated by "\n\n" (each event starts with "data: ...")
        while let Some(idx) = buffer.find("\n\n") {
            let event = buffer[..idx].trim().to_string();
            buffer = buffer[idx + 2..].to_string();

            // Each event line is like: data: {...}   OR data: [DONE]
            for line in event.lines() {
                if let Some(rest) = line.strip_prefix("data: ") {
                    if rest.trim() == "[DONE]" {
                        // Done signal
                        break;
                    } else {
                        // Parse JSON payload
                        match serde_json::from_str::<StreamResponse>(rest) {
                            Ok(parsed) => {
                                if let Some(choice) = parsed.choices.get(0) {
                                    if let Some(delta) = &choice.delta {
                                        if let Some(token) = &delta.content {
                                            // 1) append to collected_text
                                            collected_text.push_str(token);

                                            // 2) emit token to frontend with temp id
                                            let chunk_payload = serde_json::json!({
                                                "id": temp_id,
                                                "chunk": token
                                            });
                                            app_handle
                                                .emit_all("message_chunk", chunk_payload)
                                                .unwrap();
                                        }
                                    }
                                }
                            }
                            Err(e) => {
                                // parse error - log and continue
                                println!("Failed to parse stream payload: {}, payload: {}", e, rest);
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // 6) Stream finished - create final bot message in DB and emit it as usual
    let final_bot = CreateMessageInput {
        text: collected_text.clone(),
        role: MessageRole::Bot,
    };

    let saved_bot_msg =
        Message::insert_one::<CreateMessageInput>(&app_state.db, final_bot, None).await?;

    // Emit the persisted final message (frontend can use this to replace the temp message)
    app_handle
        .emit_all("message_created", &saved_bot_msg)
        .unwrap();

    // Also emit stream_end mapping temp -> final id so the frontend can reconcile
    let end_payload = serde_json::json!({
        "temp_id": temp_id,
        "final_id": saved_bot_msg._id
    });
    app_handle
        .emit_all("message_stream_end", end_payload)
        .unwrap();

    // Return the saved user message like before
    Ok(saved_user_msg)
}
```

Frontend (recommended listeners)
- message_stream_start: create a placeholder Bot message with id = temp_id and empty text.
- message_chunk: append chunk to message with id = temp_id (you can render progressively).
- message_stream_end: you‚Äôll get temp_id and final_id ‚Äî you can replace the placeholder with the final DB-backed message when you also receive the message_created event (or use the mapping to swap id).
- message_created: as before, handle saved messages from DB (user and final bot messages).

Minimal example (React + useEffect pseudo-code):

```ts
// in your component initialization
useEffect(() => {
  const un1 = listen("message_stream_start", (e) => {
    const { id } = e.payload;
    addMessage({ _id: id, text: "", role: "Bot", isTemp: true });
  });

  const un2 = listen("message_chunk", (e) => {
    const { id, chunk } = e.payload;
    appendToMessageText(id, chunk);
  });

  const un3 = listen("message_created", (e) => {
    const msg = e.payload; // persisted DB message
    upsertMessage(msg); // insert or replace
  });

  const un4 = listen("message_stream_end", (e) => {
    const { temp_id, final_id } = e.payload;
    // optional: replace temp message id with final_id, or wait for message_created
    replaceTempIdWithFinal(temp_id, final_id);
  });

  return () => {
    un1 && un1.unlisten();
    un2 && un2.unlisten();
    un3 && un3.unlisten();
    un4 && un4.unlisten();
  };
}, []);
```

Notes and gotchas
- The code above uses Uuid crate (add uuid = { version = "1", features = ["v4"] } in Cargo.toml) and futures. Add both if not present.
- We parse SSE events by splitting on "\n\n". This handles chunk boundaries even when a chunk contains a partial event because we buffer until a full event is present.
- If you want to persist intermediate updates (so the DB message updates live), you'd need an update API on your DB layer; the approach above avoids that by creating a temp placeholder and then inserting the final persisted message.
- For larger rate/throughput concerns you might throttle emitting chunks to the frontend (e.g., accumulate tokens for 50‚Äì100ms and then emit) to avoid event spam.
- Make sure to handle errors from OpenAI (non-200 status) and emit an error event to the frontend when appropriate.
- You can stream with GPT-4/3.5 models; ensure your model supports streaming. For example I used gpt-3.5-turbo in sample ‚Äî change as needed.

