Yes ‚Äî you can make a Tauri app fullscreen both at startup (config) and at runtime (JS or Rust). Below are the common options and short examples.

1) Start fullscreen from config
Add fullscreen to the window config in tauri.conf.json (or tauri.conf.json5 / tauri.conf.toml depending on your project):

tauri.conf.json (snippet)
{
  "tauri": {
    "windows": [
      {
        "title": "My App",
        "fullscreen": true,
        "decorations": true
      }
    ]
  }
}

This opens the app in native fullscreen on launch.

2) Toggle fullscreen from the frontend (recommended)
Use the official window API from @tauri-apps/api:

TypeScript / React example
import { appWindow } from '@tauri-apps/api/window';

export async function setFullscreen(on: boolean) {
  await appWindow.setFullscreen(on);
}

export async function toggleFullscreen() {
  const isFs = await appWindow.isFullscreen();
  await appWindow.setFullscreen(!isFs);
}

Call toggleFullscreen() from a button or keyboard handler (e.g., F11).

3) Toggle fullscreen from the Rust backend
You can also change fullscreen state from Rust (e.g., in a command):

use tauri::Window;

#[tauri::command]
fn toggle_fullscreen(window: Window) -> Result<(), String> {
  let is_fs = window.is_fullscreen().map_err(|e| e.to_string())?;
  window.set_fullscreen(!is_fs).map_err(|e| e.to_string())
}

Then invoke the command from the renderer:
import { invoke } from '@tauri-apps/api/tauri';
await invoke('toggle_fullscreen');

4) Keyboard shortcut (example)
- Frontend: listen for keydown (F11) and call toggleFullscreen().
- Backend: register a global shortcut in Rust with tauri::GlobalShortcutManager to call window.set_fullscreen.

Rust global shortcut sketch:
let window = app.get_window("main").unwrap();
let mut gsm = app.global_shortcut_manager();
gsm.register("F11", move || {
  let _ = window.set_fullscreen(!window.is_fullscreen().unwrap_or(false));
});

5) Platform notes / gotchas
- macOS: toggling uses the native macOS fullscreen space (can affect window sizing and menu behavior).
- If you want a borderless ‚Äúkiosk‚Äù experience, also set decorations = false and/or use other window flags.
- Some platforms treat fullscreen differently for menubar / title bar; test behavior on target OSes.
- If you need to be truly always-on-top kiosk mode, combine fullscreen with set_always_on_top / kiosk flags (platform dependent).

That‚Äôs it ‚Äî pick config for launch-time fullscreen, or use appWindow.setFullscreen / window.set_fullscreen to toggle at runtime. Want a ready-to-drop example that adds an F11 toggle button in a React + Tauri app?

On Linux the F11 key can be intercepted by the desktop environment / compositor or simply not reach your renderer, so the straightforward renderer keydown handler sometimes doesn't work. Here are ways to diagnose and reliable ways to toggle fullscreen on Ubuntu (and which to choose).

1) Quick diagnostic ‚Äî does the renderer receive F11?
Open DevTools (Ctrl+Shift+I) and run this in the console (or add it to your app):
window.addEventListener('keydown', e => console.log('keydown', e.key, e.code));
Then press F11. If you see the event logged, your renderer gets it and you can toggle fullscreen from the renderer. If nothing logs, the DE/compositor intercepted it.

2) Toggle from renderer (works if events reach your app)
Use the Tauri window API from the renderer:

import { appWindow } from '@tauri-apps/api/window';

window.addEventListener('keydown', async (e) => {
  if (e.key === 'F11') {
    e.preventDefault();
    const isFs = await appWindow.isFullscreen();
    await appWindow.setFullscreen(!isFs);
  }
});

Note: if an input has focus, the key event might be handled there ‚Äî check focus or use keydown on document/body.

3) Use a native menu accelerator (recommended)
Menu accelerators are handled by the platform and usually work reliably across DEs:

Rust snippet (setup your menu when building app):
use tauri::{CustomMenuItem, Menu, Submenu};

let toggle = CustomMenuItem::new("toggle_fullscreen".to_string(), "Toggle Fullscreen").accelerator("F11");
let menu = Menu::new().add_submenu(Submenu::new("View", tauri::Menu::new().add_item(toggle.clone())));

tauri::Builder::default()
  .menu(menu)
  .on_menu_event(|event| {
    if event.menu_item_id() == "toggle_fullscreen" {
      let window = event.window();
      let _ = window.set_fullscreen(!window.is_fullscreen().unwrap_or(false));
    }
  })
  .run( ... );

This usually works on Linux because the toolkit (GTK/etc.) wires accelerators into the app.

4) Use a global shortcut in the backend (if you need it even when app unfocused)
Tauri provides a GlobalShortcutManager. Note: global shortcuts depend on the compositor and platform; Wayland support can be limited depending on compositor.

Rust example in setup():
tauri::Builder::default().setup(|app| {
  let app_handle = app.handle();
  let window = app.get_window("main").unwrap();
  let mut gsm = app.global_shortcut_manager();
  gsm.register("F11", move || {
    // toggle fullscreen on the main window
    if let Ok(is_fs) = window.is_fullscreen() {
      let _ = window.set_fullscreen(!is_fs);
    }
  }).expect("failed to register shortcut");
  Ok(())
});

Remember to unregister on exit if you need to.

Caveats & platform notes
- Wayland: some global shortcut APIs (or certain accelerators) may not work under Wayland or require compositor support. Menu accelerators are more reliable.
- Desktop environment: GNOME or other DMs may intercept F11 or bind it themselves; if so you can pick another accelerator or instruct users to unbind the global DE shortcut.
- If input elements consume the keydown, add the listener at document level and call e.preventDefault().

Recommendation
- First test with the renderer keydown console log to see if the event gets through.
- For the most reliable experience on Linux, use a native menu accelerator (F11) or a visible UI button for fullscreen toggle. Use global shortcuts only if you need app-to-be-visible/unfocused behavior and you understand Wayland limitations.

