Short answer: yes ‚Äî on Linux you can make a Tauri app fullscreen at startup (config) or toggle it at runtime from the renderer (JS) or the backend (Rust). On Ubuntu the F11 key is often intercepted by the desktop environment, so the most reliable approaches are: a native menu accelerator or a backend global shortcut (with Wayland caveats). Below are diagnostic steps, examples (JS + Rust) and tips.

1) Diagnostic ‚Äî does your renderer receive F11?
Paste this into DevTools Console or run it in your app to see whether key events reach the webview:

```js
// js
window.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
  console.log('keydown:', e.key, e.code, 'target:', document.activeElement?.tagName);
});
```

If you see a log when pressing F11, the renderer receives it. If not, the desktop environment likely intercepts it.

2) Start fullscreen from tauri.conf.json
This opens the app in native fullscreen on launch:

```json
// tauri.conf.json (snippet)
{
  "tauri": {
    "windows": [
      {
        "label": "main",
        "title": "My App",
        "fullscreen": true,
        "decorations": true
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

3) Toggle fullscreen from the renderer (JS)
Works if the renderer receives keys or you call it from a UI button:

```js
// js - src/utils/fullscreen.js
import { appWindow } from '@tauri-apps/api/window';

export async function toggleFullscreen() {
  const isFs = await appWindow.isFullscreen();
  await appWindow.setFullscreen(!isFs);
}

// example keyboard listener
window.addEventListener('keydown', async (e) => {
  if (e.key === 'F11') {
    e.preventDefault();
    await toggleFullscreen();
  }
});
```

4) Toggle fullscreen from the Rust backend (command)
Call this command from the frontend or trigger it from Rust logic:

```rust
// rust - src/main.rs (tauri command)
use tauri::Window;

#[tauri::command]
fn toggle_fullscreen(window: Window) -> Result<(), String> {
  let is_fs = window.is_fullscreen().map_err(|e| e.to_string())?;
  window.set_fullscreen(!is_fs).map_err(|e| e.to_string())
}
```

Invoke from JS:

```js
// js
import { invoke } from '@tauri-apps/api/tauri';
await invoke('toggle_fullscreen');
```

5) Use a native menu accelerator (recommended on Linux)
Accelerators are handled by the toolkit and are usually reliable even if F11 is stolen by the DE:

```rust
// rust - src/main.rs (menu accelerator)
use tauri::{CustomMenuItem, Menu, Submenu, Manager};

fn main() {
  let toggle = CustomMenuItem::new("toggle_fullscreen".to_string(), "Toggle Fullscreen")
    .accelerator("F11");
  let view = Submenu::new("View", Menu::new().add_item(toggle.clone()));
  let menu = Menu::new().add_submenu(view);

  tauri::Builder::default()
    .menu(menu)
    .on_menu_event(|event| {
      if event.menu_item_id() == "toggle_fullscreen" {
        let window = event.window();
        if let Ok(is_fs) = window.is_fullscreen() {
          let _ = window.set_fullscreen(!is_fs);
        }
      }
    })
    .run(tauri::generate_context!())
    .expect("error while running tauri application");
}
```

6) Global shortcut (works even when unfocused, but Wayland caveats)
Register in setup. Note: Wayland/compositor limitations vary ‚Äî global shortcuts may fail under Wayland depending on user/session.

```rust
// rust - src/main.rs (register global shortcut in setup)
use tauri::{Manager, GlobalShortcutManager};

fn main() {
  tauri::Builder::default()
    .setup(|app| {
      let window = app.get_window("main").unwrap();
      let mut gsm = app.global_shortcut_manager();
      let w = window.clone();

      gsm.register("F11", move || {
        if let Ok(is_fs) = w.is_fullscreen() {
          let _ = w.set_fullscreen(!is_fs);
        }
      }).expect("failed to register global shortcut");

      Ok(())
    })
    .run(tauri::generate_context!())
    .expect("error while running tauri application");
}
```

7) Kiosk / borderless fullscreen tips
If you want a borderless or kiosk-like experience combine fullscreen with removing decorations and (optionally) always-on-top:

```rust
// rust - examples for kiosk-like behavior
let _ = window.set_decorations(false); // remove title bar / borders
let _ = window.set_fullscreen(true);   // fullscreen
let _ = window.set_always_on_top(true); // keep on top (if desired)
```

Or from JS (where supported via the window API wrapper):

```js
// js (if your Tauri JS wrapper exposes these)
import { appWindow } from '@tauri-apps/api/window';
await appWindow.setFullscreen(true);
await appWindow.setDecorations(false);
```

Note: Some decoration/always-on-top APIs are more reliably invoked from Rust.

8) Troubleshooting & platform notes
- If F11 is captured by the DE (e.g., GNOME), try a different key, use menu accelerators, or ask users to unbind the DE shortcut.
- Wayland: global shortcuts and some window tricks can be restricted by the compositor. Menu accelerators and in-app buttons are safer.
- If a focused input consumes the key event, attach the listener to document and test in different focus states.
- Test on both X11 and Wayland (Ubuntu setups vary).
- Packaging: ensure your window label matches the one you reference (get_window("main") vs label in tauri.conf).

Recommendation
- First run the diagnostic snippet to confirm whether the renderer gets F11.
- If it does, the renderer toggle is simplest.
- If not, use a native menu accelerator (F11) in Rust ‚Äî that‚Äôs the most reliable approach on Linux.
- Use global shortcuts only if you need behavior while unfocused and you accept Wayland limitations.

