Short answer first
- Quick checks (Linux): ps / pmap / /proc/<pid>/status or htop/smem for realtime.
- Programmatic (recommended for a Tauri app): query the process from the Rust side (sysinfo or procfs) and expose a tauri command the renderer can call.
- Caveats: RSS vs virtual memory vs PSS; shared pages can be double-counted; platform values differ.

Quick OS commands

Linux
- Get RSS (resident set size) and VSZ (virtual size) for PID:
```bash
ps -p <PID> -o pid,comm,%mem,rss,vsz
```
- Check /proc for RSS and VmSize:
```bash
grep -E 'VmRSS|VmSize' /proc/<PID>/status
```
- pmap summary (RSS in KB):
```bash
pmap -x <PID> | tail -n1
```
- Real-time, interactive: htop or top:
```bash
htop   # or
top -p <PID>
```
- For proportional-set-size (PSS, more accurate for shared pages) use smem:
```bash
smem -p -P <process-name-or-PID>
```

macOS
- top snapshot:
```bash
top -pid <PID> -l 1 -stats pid,command,rsize,vsize
```
- ps:
```bash
ps -p <PID> -o pid,rss,vsz,command
```
- Activity Monitor and Instruments (Allocations/Leaks) give GUI and profiling options.

Windows
- Task Manager or Resource Monitor.
- PowerShell:
```powershell
Get-Process -Id <PID> | Select-Object Id,ProcessName,WS,PM,VM
```
(WS = Working Set = physical memory in bytes)

Programmatic approach for Tauri (recommended)
- Run this from Rust in your Tauri backend and expose it as a command. The example uses the sysinfo crate to return RSS and virtual memory (in bytes) plus PID.

Cargo.toml
```toml
[dependencies]
tauri = { version = "1", features = ["api-all"] } # match your tauri version
sysinfo = "0.29" # or latest compatible
serde = { version = "1", features = ["derive"] }
```

Rust: src/main.rs (command to return memory)
```rust
use serde::Serialize;
use sysinfo::{PidExt, ProcessExt, System, SystemExt};
use tauri::Manager;

#[derive(Serialize)]
struct MemInfo {
  pid: u32,
  rss_bytes: u64,
  virtual_bytes: u64,
  // optional: memory_kb: u64,
}

#[tauri::command]
fn get_memory_info() -> Result<MemInfo, String> {
  let mut sys = System::new();
  // refresh the process info only
  let pid_u32 = std::process::id();
  let pid = sysinfo::Pid::from(pid_u32 as usize);
  sys.refresh_process(pid);

  if let Some(p) = sys.process(pid) {
    // sysinfo returns memory values in KB on many platforms
    let rss_kb = p.memory();
    let vsize_kb = p.virtual_memory();
    Ok(MemInfo {
      pid: pid_u32,
      rss_bytes: rss_kb.saturating_mul(1024),
      virtual_bytes: vsize_kb.saturating_mul(1024),
    })
  } else {
    Err("process info not found".into())
  }
}

fn main() {
  tauri::Builder::default()
    .invoke_handler(tauri::generate_handler![get_memory_info])
    .run(tauri::generate_context!())
    .expect("error while running tauri");
}
```

Renderer (React/JS): call the command and display
```js
import { invoke } from '@tauri-apps/api/tauri';
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

function MemoryPanel() {
  const [mem, setMem] = useState(null);

  async function refresh() {
    try {
      const info = await invoke('get_memory_info');
      setMem(info);
    } catch (e) {
      console.error(e);
    }
  }

  useEffect(() => {
    refresh();
    const id = setInterval(refresh, 2000); // poll every 2s if you want live updates
    return () => clearInterval(id);
  }, []);

  if (!mem) return <div>Loading...</div>;

  return (
    <div>
      <div>PID: {mem.pid}</div>
      <div>RSS: {(mem.rss_bytes / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(2)} MB</div>
      <div>Virtual: {(mem.virtual_bytes / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(2)} MB</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Alternative: read /proc/self/status (Linux-only, more direct)
- You can read and parse /proc/self/status or /proc/self/statm in Rust if you want a tiny dependency and raw values (VmRSS, VmSize, etc.). For accurate PSS, parse /proc/<pid>/smaps (heavy).

Advanced notes and caveats
- RSS vs Virtual: RSS = resident physical memory in RAM. VSZ/virtual includes mapped files, reserved address space, etc.
- Shared pages: libraries and shared memory are counted into RSS for each process ‚Äî PSS is better for per-process ‚Äúreal‚Äù memory but requires parsing smaps.
- sysinfo memory units: ProcessExt::memory() typically returns KB; we multiply by 1024 to return bytes in the example.
- Peak memory: to get peak, on Linux check /proc/<pid>/status VmHWM (High Water Mark) or use getrusage(RUSAGE_SELF) for maxrss (units vary).
- For profiling allocations inside Rust, use tools like heaptrack, massif, valgrind, or install an allocator with stats (jemalloc with stats).
- If your app spawns child processes (e.g., local LLM backend), measure those PIDs too or sum them.

Which approach fits you?
- Quick ad-hoc check: use htop/ps/pmap/smem.
- In-app display or telemetry: use the Rust sysinfo command + Tauri invoke (the snippet above).
- Deep profiling: use platform profilers (Instruments/macOS, heaptrack/valgrind/Linux, Windows Performance Toolkit).

